1. What Are Artifacts:
    - Artifacts are the output of your build process—the packaged, deployable version of your application.
    - For a Node.js app, artifacts could be:
        Docker images: a container image containing Node.js, your app code, and dependencies.
        NPM packages: .tgz files if you’re publishing your Node.js library.
        Binaries: precompiled executables (less common for Node.js).
        Other files: JARs, WARs, zip/tar archives in other languages.
    - Artifacts are crucial because they provide a stable, reproducible build that can be deployed across environments (staging, production).

2. Tagging Artifacts:
    - Tagging is how you identify a specific version of your artifact. Common strategies:
    a. Git Commit Hashes
        - Tag the artifact with the short commit SHA.
        - Example: my-node-app:abc1234
        - Pros:
            Direct traceability to code.
            Every artifact is unique.
        - Cons:
            Harder for humans to remember.
    b. Semantic Versioning (SemVer)
        - Format: MAJOR.MINOR.PATCH → 1.2.3
        - Example: my-node-app:1.2.3
        - Rules:
            MAJOR → breaking changes
            MINOR → new features, backward compatible
            PATCH → bug fixes
        - Pros:
            Easy for humans to understand.
            Works well for release management.
    c. Combined Approach
        - Some teams combine both: my-node-app:1.2.3-abc1234
        - You see both semantic version and exact commit.

3. Storing Artifacts:
    - Artifacts need a central repository so they can be reused across environments. Common options:
    Tool	            Artifact Type	                Notes
    Docker Registry	    Docker images	                Most Node.js apps today use Docker for deployment.
    Nexus Repository	Docker, npm, Maven, binaries	Supports multiple formats.
    Artifactory	        Docker, npm, binaries	        Enterprise-grade artifact repository.
    GitHub Packages	    npm packages, Docker images	    Integrated with GitHub CI/CD.
    - Workflow Example for a Node.js App using Docker:
        - CI pipeline builds the Docker image:
            docker build -t my-node-app:1.2.3 .
        - Tag with commit SHA:
            docker tag my-node-app:1.2.3 my-node-app:abc1234
        - Push to artifact repository:
            docker push my-docker-registry/my-node-app:1.2.3
            docker push my-docker-registry/my-node-app:abc1234
        - CD pipeline pulls the exact artifact version for deployment:
            docker pull my-docker-registry/my-node-app:1.2.3

